The '''''Dieulacres Chronicle''''' is a 14th century [[England in the Middle Ages|English]] [[chronicle]] that was written at the [[Cistercian]] [[Dieulacres Abbey]] in [[Staffordshire]]. It has three parts: the first is a description of England that borrows from [[Bede]], [[Ranulf Higden]] and [[Gerald of Wales]]; the second is a history of the [[earl]]s of [[earl of Chester|Chester]] and Dieulacres Abbey dating to the 13th century; and the third is a history of England spanning the years from 1337-1403.<ref>{{Cite journal| last = Kennedy| first = Edward Donald| title = Dieulacres chronicle 1337-1403| accessdate = 2018-02-11| date = 2016-09-13| url = http://referenceworks.brillonline.com/entries/encyclopedia-of-the-medieval-chronicle/dieulacres-chronicle-1337-1403-SIM_00887}}</ref> After [[Henry Bolingbroke]] and [[Thomas Arundel]] invaded England and deposed [[Richard II]], a number of chronicles, including Dieulacres were edited by newly appointed scribes to support Henry's [[House of Lancaster|Lancastrian]] claim to the throne.<ref>{{Cite book| publisher = Boydell & Brewer Ltd| isbn = 978-1-903153-53-6| last1 = Horobin| first1 = Simon| last2 = Mooney| first2 = Linne R.| title = Middle English Texts in Transition: A Festschrift Dedicated to Toshiyuki Takamiya on His 70th Birthday| date = 2014}}</ref>
==References== {{reflist}}
[[Category:English chronicles]]

{{italic title}}
'''''Frahang-i Ōīm-Ēwak'''''<ref>{{IPA|[fɾaˈhaŋg iː oːˈiːm eːˈwakʰ]}}</ref> is an old [[Avestan]]-[[Middle Persian]] [[dictionary]]. It is named with the two first words of the dictionary: ''ōīm'' in Avestan means 'one' and ''ēwak'' is its Pahlavi equivalent. It gives the Pahlavi meanings of about 880 Avestan words, either by one word or one phrase or by explaining it.

==External links==
* [http://www.rahamasha.net/uploads/2/3/2/8/2328777/avesta_glossary_text.pdf Raham Asha: Avesta Glossary. A glossary of Avesta words and their Pārsīg equivalents, based on the Zand, the so-called ''Frahang ī ōīm:ēk''. Text and Grammatical Notes. Mumbai, The K. R. Cama Oriental Institute, 2009.]{{dead link|date=August 2012}}

